Sure! Here's an example of entropy loading for DMT modulation using water filling method in MATLAB with 8 subchannels and a maximum number of 8 bits per subchannel.

```matlab
% Define the system parameters
N_subchannels = 8;
N_bits_max = 8;
SNR_dB = 20; % signal-to-noise ratio in dB
SNR = 10.^(SNR_dB/10); % convert SNR to linear scale

% Generate random data to be transmitted
data = randi([0 1], N_bits_max, N_subchannels);

% Calculate the channel capacity for each subchannel using water-filling algorithm
power_alloc = waterfill(SNR*ones(1,N_subchannels), 1/N_subchannels);
capacity = log2(1+SNR*power_alloc');

% Calculate the entropy for each subchannel
p = power_alloc./sum(power_alloc);
entropy = -1*sum(p.*log2(p))/log2(N_bits_max);

% Allocate bit rate to each subchannel using the entropy loading algorithm
bit_alloc = zeros(N_bits_max, N_subchannels);
for i=1:N_subchannels
    % Calculate the target number of bits for this subchannel
    target_bits = round(N_bits_max * entropy * capacity(i)/sum(capacity));

    % Allocate the required number of bits to this subchannel using water-filling algorithm
    bit_alloc(:,i) = waterfill(SNR*power_alloc', target_bits)';
end

% Truncate the allocated bits to the maximum number of bits per subchannel
bit_alloc(bit_alloc > N_bits_max) = N_bits_max;

% Transmit the data using the allocated bit rate
transmit_data = zeros(N_bits_max, N_subchannels);
for i=1:N_subchannels
    transmit_data(:,i) = data(1:bit_alloc(i),i);
end

% Add padding to the transmitted data to make it the same length for each subchannel
transmit_data(N_bits_max+1:end,:) = [];

% Perform DMT modulation on the transmitted data for each subchannel
signal = zeros(1, N_subchannels);
for i=1:N_subchannels
    signal(i,:) = ifft(transmit_data(:,i));
end
```

In this example, the system parameters and random data are generated first. The channel capacity is then calculated for each subchannel using the water-filling algorithm, and the entropy is calculated based on the probability distribution of the capacity values.

The bit rate is then allocated to each subchannel using the entropy loading algorithm, where the target number of bits for each subchannel is determined by the channel capacity, entropy, and the total number of allocated bits. The allocated bit rate is obtained using the water-filling algorithm again.

The allocated bit rate is then truncated to the maximum number of bits per subchannel, and the data is transmitted using the allocated bit rate, the DMT modulation for each subchannel is then performed.

Note that this is just an example, and the exact implementation may depend on the specific details of the system you are working with.

